Without loss of generality, assume that $F_1 F_2 = 2,$ so $c = 1.$  Since triangle $QF_1 F_2$ is equilateral, $b = \sqrt{3}$ and $a = 2.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, M;
pair[] F;
real a, b, c, s;

a = 5;
b = sqrt(3)/2*5;
c = 5/2;
s = 8;

A = (-s/2,-sqrt(3)/2*(s - 5));
B = (0,b);
C = (s/2,-sqrt(3)/2*(s - 5));
F[1] = (c,0);
F[2] = (-c,0);
M = (A + C)/2;

draw(yscale(b)*xscale(a)*Circle((0,0),1));
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw((-a,0)--(a,0));
draw((0,-b)--(0,b));

